# CQRS Messaging Pattern

Use CQRS-style messaging conventions in the application layer.

## Commands

- Commands represent intent to change state.
- Name them `*Command`.
- Handle them in `*CommandHandler`.
- Commands should be immutable request objects.

## Queries

- Queries represent read requests.
- Name them `*Query`.
- Handle them in `*QueryHandler`.
- Queries should return read DTOs, lists, or projections.
- Query handlers should prefer dedicated read repositories for flat response models once query access is more than trivial.
- In read repositories, prefer DBAL QueryBuilder over raw SQL strings by default.
- Use raw SQL only when QueryBuilder becomes materially worse for the query shape or database-specific optimization.
- Do not force query handlers through aggregate repositories when the use case only needs a flat read model.

## Handler Rules

- Command handlers use repositories + domain methods + save + domain event dispatch.
- Query handlers use read-optimized access and should not mutate state.
- Keep handlers focused on one use case.

## Return Rules

- Prefer `Result` / `ResultWithValue`.
- Expected business failures should be returned, not thrown.

## Read/Write Access Split

- Command side should use aggregate repositories.
- Query side should prefer read-optimized access.
- If query complexity grows, introduce dedicated read repositories instead of reusing aggregate repositories blindly.
- Keep SQL construction in read repositories, not in query handlers.
- Do not hydrate full Doctrine aggregates on query side just to flatten them into response DTOs.
